<TEXT>
snow and sleet blanketed much of southern 
california thursday and dozens of cars crashed on an icy mountain 
interstate killing two people the snow also blocked thousands of 
motorists on a coastal highway 
snow flurries appeared in the southern san joaquin valley and 
sleet and rain fell around los angeles including hills that were 
dry and ablaze only a week ago as the storm swept from nevada 
across californias midsection 
as temperatures headed down to the 40s for the night los angeles 
gave hotel vouchers to homeless people and opened shelters in a 
recreation center and an armory two armories opened as shelters in 
orange county 
ten crashes involving dozens of vehicles and two deaths occurred 
on interstate 15 in cajon pass said highway patrol spokesman john 
savage no information was immediately available on the deaths 
at midmorning police began slowly escorting groups of cars 
through the pass behind snowplows rather than require use of chains 
which causes miles of backup and hours of delay 
its just like a winter wonderland up there said officer jim 
roden 
thousands of motorists were stuck when snow closed highway 101 
north of san luis obispo which is about 150 miles north of los 
angeles police said 
one of the problems is here we dont have the snow equipment to 
take care of this it doesnt happen here said chp officer frank 
stricker 
cuesta summit is only 1500 feet above sea level and stricker 
noted snow fell not only at the top but at the bottom of the grade 
as well 
a college basketball game between san francisco state and cal 
polysan luis obispo was canceled because the san francisco team was 
stranded at atascadero on the north side of the grade said cal poly 
official lisa boyer 
motel rooms filled up fast in atascadero and paso robles as the 
highway traffic ground to a halt said frances davis who works at 
the paso robles inn it was the first snowfall ms davis had seen 
there in 22 years 
interstate 5 over the tejon pass north of los angeles was snowy 
and slick but the major northsouth route through the san gabriels 
remained open 
the storm was generated by a cold upperlevel low over nevada 
that moved through central california the national weather service 
said the low was expected to drift west on friday 
downtown los angeles warmed only to 56 degrees thursday compared 
to a normal of 68 rainfall totaled 77 inch by 6 pm bringing the 
season total to 156 inches compared to a normal 329 inches by dec 
15 
elsewhere rainfall totaled 169 inches at mount wilson 168 
inches at newhall 95 inch at pasadena and 114 inch at point mugu 
by evening 
just a week earlier the los angeles basin was swept by warm and 
fierce santa ana winds dozens of homes were burned by windblown 
fires in two suburbs on dec 8 and the next day more burned in a 
3000acre brush fire in the santa susana mountains above the 
northern san fernando valley 
snow flurries were reported on the floor of the southern san 
joaquin valley at bakersfield taft and mcfarland the weather 
service said 
snowfall ranged from 2 to 6 inches in northern san luis obispo 
county and some schools were closed said sheriffs lt jerry dooley 
of course people in this area arent prepared for snow he 
said 
