wednesday that 58 percent of homeowners had a first mortgage and 11 
percent had other loans secured by their equity or the value of the 
home beyond what is owed on it 
the julynovember survey of 2510 households found that 
traditional second mortgages loans for a fixed amount to be repaid 
on a fixed schedule were held by 5 percent of the homeowners the 
newer home equity lines of credit which allow people to borrow 
money at their discretion up to an approved credit limit were held 
by 6 percent 
eightyfour percent of the homeowners with loans secured by their 
equity listed foreclosure as a risk should they be unable to repay 
the money and another 6 percent to 7 percent mentioned other legal 
actions as a possibility said richard t curtin director of the 
universitys surveys of consumers 
their caution in using their home equity line of credit 
comes out of this understanding of the consequences of missing 
payments he said 
among families with approved lines of credit 31 percent had not 
borrowed any money either because the planned need for the money 
had not arisen or because the credit line was meant to serve as a 
cash reserve in case of emergency according to the survey 
among those who had borrowed against their lines of credit the 
median outstanding debt was just 10 percent of net home equity 
although the median amount the families had authorization to borrow 
was 32 percent of net equity 
theyre well aware that theyre betting their home and theyre 
very cautious about it curtin said 
some consumer groups have criticized banks for advertising low 
rates on home equity loans that are available only for a short 
period and for failing to disclose important information about 
conditions and fees on the loans 
michelle meier of the private consumers union said the 
suggestion that consumers generally know the risks they are assuming 
is not justified by the surveys findings 
we think there are a lot of problems she said even 
consumers who are aware of the risk of foreclosure may be surprised 
by changing repayment plans rising interest rates and other 
conditions that could make it more difficult to repay their loans 
she said 
the university of michigan survey was supported by 35 
corporations financial institutions and trade associations with an 
interest in home equity loans curtin discussed the results at a 
news conference sponsored by the american financial services 
association and the us league of savings institutions two of the 
groups that helped finance the survey 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

