<TEXT>
major us jewish groups warily supported the reagan 
administrations historic decision to sit down with the palestine 
liberation organization while arabamericans said the policy 
reversal rekindled hope for middle east peace 
several american jewish leaders said they trusted president 
reagan and secretary of state george p shultz in their decision to 
open a substantive dialogue with the plo but called on plo 
chairman yasser arafat to back his words of peace with action 
we understand that the united states having set standards for 
speaking with the plo and the plo having met those minimum 
standards that it is appropriate for us to live up to its 
commitment said abraham h foxman national director of the 
antidefamation league of bnai brith in new york 
it is a first step now we must watch to see if the plo will 
match words with deeds 
james zogby executive director of the arabamerican institute in 
washington called the governments decision to end its longtime 
rejection of the plo as a party to middle east peace efforts an 
important step forward 
the dialogue should throw into sharp relief the failure of 
israel to say yes to the very issues that the plo has now acceded 
to zogby said our hope is that the dialogue is productive and 
that peace is now possible 
in washington legislators from both parties cautiously endorsed 
the move 
it may be a blind alley but an alley worth treading with eyes 
open said sen richard lugar rind this dialogue in no way 
mitigates our steadfast support of israel but i hope israel will at 
least be willing to informally acknowledge this process as a worthy 
attempt 
in the interest of peace and security for israel and all 
parties in the region the us has no sensible choice but to begin 
a dialogue said us rep david obey dwis chairman of the 
house foreign operations appropriations subcommittee 
but he added the proof will still lie in deeds and not 
words 
atlanta mayor andrew young who nearly a decade ago was forced by 
thenpresident carter to resign as the us ambassador to the united 
