the justice department says employers whose 
workers are killed or injured on the job can be prosecuted for 
murder manslaughter or assault under state laws and cannot seek 
refuge under federal workplace safety laws 
the department in an opinion released wednesday in response to a 
request from a congressional committee said criminal penalties in 
the 1970 occupational safety and health act do not preempt state 
and local criminal laws 
we see nothing in the act or its legislative history which 
indicates that congress intended for the relatively limited criminal 
penalties provided by the act to deprive employees of the protection 
provided by state criminal laws of general applicability the 
department said 
the opinion flies in the face of several recent state court 
rulings throwing out criminal convictions against employers whose 
workers were injured through violations of federal job safety 
standards 
