<TEXT>
lyndon larouches fraud conspiracy trial 
went to the jury today for a verdict on whether he schemed to cheat 
tax collectors and lenders who supported his controversial causes 
after final closing arguments by defense lawyers and a rebuttal 
by government prosecutors chief us district judge albert v bryan 
jr sent the case to the jury of eight women and four men who heard 
testimony during the 15day trial 
bryan said the jurors will deliberate saturday if necessary to 
reach a verdict 
larouche the 66yearold political maverick and perennial 
minorparty presidential candidate did not testify in his own 
defense 
defense lawyer michael reilly said larouche fundraisers 
solicited loans with good faith assurances that they would be 
repaid but assistant us attorney kent robinson said all the 
defendants knew the terms of the loans could not be honored 
robinson told the jurors in the governments rebuttal that 
supporters who loaned money to the larouche movement werent the 
lifeblood of this organization these supporters were bled dry 
the organization treated these people with cynicism and 
disregard because everyone knew that the larouche organization was 
a bankruptcy waiting to happen he said 
the result robinson said was an enormous crime a 30 
million crime 
bryan cautioned the jurors in his instructions that larouches 
political goals were irrelevant to the case and robinson insisted 
that the government was not trying to get at lyndon larouche or 
quiet a political movement 
larouches political movement embraces a number of unorthodox 
positions and relies heavily on conspiracy theories to explain world 
events it has alleged that figures such as henry kissinger and 
queen elizabeth participate in those conspiracies larouche backers 
also have advocated a quarantine for aids victims 
a halfdozen defense attorneys heaped abuse on the governments 
case against larouche and six associates as garbage and a 
rotting carcass during closing arguments tuesday 
but prosecutors said they had proved that the defendants had 
conspired to defraud larouche supporters by raising more than 30 
million in loans without any intention of repaying them 
in addition larouche is charged with conspiring to defraud the 
internal revenue service by having all his personal expenses paid by 
various corporations he controls and pretending he had no taxable 
income 
if convicted on all 13 counts against him larouche faces a 
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling 325 
million larouche and his aides deny any wrongdoing 
prosecutor john markham said the governments case had nothing to 
do with larouches political beliefs but focused on allegedly 
deceptive fundraising practices 
the ends however noble they may be do not justify lying to 
people to get their money markham declared 
he said larouches lenders were burned by a group of people who 
think they are better and can use the money better than anyone 
else 
but larouche attorney odin anderson of boston said the 
governments case was based on voodoo conspiracy charges that 
were vague and unfounded 
they dont want you to decide straightforward facts anderson 
told the jurors they want you to decide garbage 
anderson said the bad smell that sometimes wafted through the 
courtroom came from the rotting carcass of the governments case 
at one point the judge admonished defense lawyer brian gettings 
for shouting at the jury during an especially impassioned closing 
argument 
hunched over his arms flailing and his fingers waggling 
gettings branded as liars two crucial government witnesses 
both former employees of the larouche organization who he said 
were openly vehemently hostile to every defendant in this case 
gettings said the defendants had simply borrowed too much money 
and were unable to repay loans because of government harassment and 
media attacks that shrank their revenues 
larouche and his fundraisers werent trying to line their 
pockets like classic fraud defendants gettings said if you dont 
find greed its impossible to find fraud he said 
defense lawyer james clark said the larouche case wasnt about 
money but about a political movement with dedicated followers who 
want it to succeed and powerful enemies who want it to fail 
anderson claimed the fbi actually wrote the letter that an 
elderly connecticut woman sent to larouche demanding the return of 
her loan money anderson said the letter was an fbi entrapment 
attempt against larouche 
 
