<TEXT>
the government does not need evidence of drug 
abuse to justify random tests of federal officials with access to 
classified information the justice department told an appeals court 
thursday 
deterrence of drug use among officials in a position to 
compromise secrets is justification enough to randomly test them 
assistant attorney general john h bolton said 
the united states is permitted as an employer to make 
reasonable steps to prevent something from becoming a problem 
bolton said challenging a lower courts ban on random testing of 
4700 justice department officials 
there are enormous national security interests at stake here 
bolton told a threejudge panel of the us circuit court of 
appeals the lower courts ruling stopped the drugtesting program 
from being implemented last summer 
this is a case about protecting the integrity of those who 
represent the united states in court bolton said its a case 
about protecting national security safeguarding grand jury secrecy 
and preserving the efficacy of criminal prosecution 
the context is a fitnessforduty test by a public employer 
bolton said of the program that is being challenged by employees who 
obtained a permanent injunction barring the tests from us district 
judge george revercomb 
former maryland attorney general stephen h sachs urged the panel 
to uphold revercombs finding that testing without any suspicion of 
drug use by the individual is an unconstitutional invasion of 
privacy 
sachs said the appeals court was mandated to weigh and to 
balance the governments interest in testing with the individual 
employees constitutional rights to privacy 
in doing so the court must ask is there a demonstrable 
existence of a problem he said 
the justice department has failed to provide some kind of data 
that supports the reasonableness of the search and that is the 
core command of the fourth amendment said sachs who was once 
us attorney in baltimore 
the employees dont dispute the need to preserve the departments 
integrity or protect secrets sachs said the question is how may 
the department go about enforcing and imposing those accepted 
requirements 
the department has plenty of ways observation of supervisors 
background checks all the less intrusive ways to check up on its 
employees sachs said 
but bolton argued that the issue was not evidence of drug use but 
the types of secrets the employees handled 
justice department employees have access to some of the nations 
most closely held secrets such as information about 
counterintelligence and defense programs such as the stealth 
bomber 
stealth technology is something that the kgb would crawl over 
hot coals to get its hands on bolton said 
but his argument seemed to trouble chief judge patricia wald who 
questioned when those national security concerns would justify an 
intrusive search 
the strongest part of your case is the governments interest 
wald told bolton its the other side of the equation what can 
trigger this type of testing that bothers me the most 
theres no question we are living in a highrisk society the 
question is how far can we go in deterring large risks in terms 
of our constitutional rights wald said 
bolton argued that justice department employees already waived 
privacy rights when they submitted to extensive fbi background 
checks and medical examinations 
circuit judge laurence silberman taking up an argument advanced 
by bolton suggested that requiring evidence of drug use would mean 
the government would have to stop testing once it had successfully 
deterred narcotics abuse among a group of employees 
the implications of that argument are awful sachs said 
the government could suspend the constitution if deterrence 
were allowed to be the sole justification for drug testing he said 
both sides urged the court to decide the case without waiting for 
a ruling by the supreme court on two other cases involving drug 
testing the high court is reviewing testing of us customs service 
agents seeking promotion and railway crews involved in accidents 
circuit judge spottswood robinson iii also sat on the panel 
which gave no indication when it would rule 
