a city ordinance requiring handgun purchasers 
to wait 15 days before picking up their weapons goes into effect 
friday 
the law requires the wait between sale and receipt of a handgun 
to allow police time to check whether the prospective buyer has a 
criminal record or is mentally incompetent 
until now guns could be picked up immediately and police had to 
track the buyers down if there were reasons to prevent them from 
buying guns cincinnatis ordinance is based on an ohio law that 
allows cities to enact local gun control measures 
the national rifle association which lobbied against the 
ordinance said cincinnatis law goes farther than measures in other 
cities because it applies to individuals who sell guns as well as 
to commercial gun dealers 
the law requires anyone selling renting leasing or transferring 
ownership or possession of a handgun to notify police of the 
transaction and fill out an application form forms are available at 
police district stations and the city safety department offices 
the ordinance does not cover rifles or shotguns 
violation is a firstdegree misdemeanor with a maximum 1000 
fine and six months in jail 
three stores in cincinnati now sell handguns retailers say it is 
too soon to tell what impact the ordinance will have on sales 
