film censors in their first open meeting ever 
approved a controversial movie about a young man who cannot cope 
with chinas new competition and commits suicide an official paper 
said thursday 
the censors decided that the movie tentatively titled 
transmigration can be released uncut to chinese theaters the 
guangming daily said 
the movie is directed by huang jianxin and produced by the xian 
film studio which in recent years has produced chinas most 
technically innovative and politically daring films 
huangs first feature movie the black cannon incident in 
1985 was cut by censors but still caused an uproar with its attack 
on mindless bureaucracy it told the story of a telegraphed message 
about a missing chess piece that was misinterpreted by officials as 
a message about a real cannon 
the guangming daily said censors in the ministry of radio film 
and television discussed huangs new movie in a twohour session 
that was open to journalists for the first time it did not say if 
the censors plan to make all their meetings open 
few chinese films have dealt with the impact on ordinary lives of 
the economic reforms of the past decade in which central planning 
and social welfare guarantees have been reduced in favor of the free 
market 
although the incomes of most chinese have risen dramatically 
some have actually slid and many people are unable or unwilling to 
obtain jobs or promotions based on merit 
by showing the underside of the new competition in which some 
cant keep up huangs movie could be seen as an indirect attack on 
government policy but he said in an interview earlier this year 
that this was not his intent 
the 34yearold director said his goal was not to provoke 
controversy but to make films that reflect social problems so 
they can be corrected 
the guangming daily said the censors decided that the movie is 
an authentic and honest attempt to portray the reactions of young 
people to the reform era in china and has artistic appeal 
for decades censors met privately and without objective 
guidelines to rule on the acceptability of movies and other 
entertainment the ministry of culture is drafting a law that would 
establish rules for what is permissible 
although this would reduce the power of individual censors some 
artists have expressed fears the law will halt the current process 
of gradual experimentation and liberalization 
