<TEXT>
the judge in the irancontra case on thursday 
scheduled a hearing for dec 21 to begin making final preparations 
for the trial of former white house aide oliver l north 
us district judge gerhard a gesell who has previously 
indicated the trial could begin as early as late january said in an 
order that he wanted to discuss procedures for screening potential 
jurors and other pretrial housekeeping matters 
the scheduling order provided yet another indication that gesell 
is determined to take the case to a speedy trial 
on monday he strictly limited the number of classified documents 
that north can introduce into evidence and set a jan 3 deadline for 
listing those secrets he would propose to disclose at the trial 
gesells rulings on secret documents earlier this week greatly 
increased the likelihood that all the charges against the former 
national security council aide will go to trial despite reagan 
administration refusal to release secret documents the defense wants 
to publicly disclose 
under the classified information procedures act gesell could 
still dismiss the central conspiracy charge against north if he 
determines that the withheld documents are needed to ensure that 
north gets a fair trial 
but the judge made clear that he would not allow north to 
introduce documents that were not relevant to his defense simply to 
scuttle his prosecution 
north is accused of conspiring to illegally divert usiran 
armssale profits to the contra rebels in nicaragua 
he faces a total of 14 felony counts including charges he lied 
to congress destroyed documents pocketed travelers checks intended 
for the contra leaders and illegally used a taxexempt foundation to 
raise money to arm the rebels 
three codefendants are set to be tried separately after north 
at next weeks hearing the judge said he wanted to consider the 
type of questionnaire that would be sent to prospective jurors 
gesell said he also wanted to set a deadline for independent 
counsel lawrence e walsh to provide norths lawyers with the grand 
jury testimony of the prosecution witnesses the defense is entitled 
to examine that testimony to prepare cross examination 
questionnaires are usually sent to jurors for lengthy or 
highprofile criminal cases such as the perjury trial of former 
white house aide michael k deaver 
the questions are designed to screen out jurors who would be 
unable to serve for a variety of reasons including their inability 
to render a fair verdict or to understand complicated evidence 
the completed questionnaires would be used as a basis to conduct 
jury selection in court 
the north trial which could last several months may require the 
court to order as many as 1000 questionnaires to screen out people 
who are unable to serve for the duration of the proceeding 
the questionnaire would likely also ask prospective jurors 
whether they could judge the evidence in the case free of any 
influence from the extensive publicity that has surrounded the 
irancontra affair 
