for the second consecutive year fluecured 
tobacco farmers in 1989 will see a hefty boost in federal marketing 
quotas the agriculture department announced thursday 
deputy secretary peter c myers said the 1989 fluecured quota 
will be 8905 million pounds up 18 percent from this years 755 
million pounds the national acreage allotment will be increased to 
426485 acres from 379588 acres in 1988 
allowing for overmarketings and undermarketings the effective 
quota for 1989 will be up by about 90 million pounds from this year 
myers said the fluecured price support will be boosted to 1468 
per pound an increase of 26 cents from 1988 
the basic quota was increased on the 1988 fluecured tobacco crop 
for the first time since 1975 according to usda analysts 
reflecting a drawdown on stockpiles and brisk demand 
myers said fluecured tobacco farmers will vote in a mail 
referendum to be held jan 912 on whether to continue federal 
marketing quotas for the following three years 1990 1991 and 1992 
a twothirds majority will be required for the controls to continue 
