<TEXT>
federal election officials under court order 
to clarify how political parties can spend campaign funds heard 
democratic and republican spokesman warn thursday that too much 
regulation could stamp out politicking at the local level 
while other critics told the federal election commission that 
current rules have led to illegal use of socalled soft money the 
national political parties lobbied for flexibility in what the state 
and local parties can do 
the issue revolves around how to apply the federal election laws 
to the local entities who get money from the national parties and 
whose activity can provide overlapping benefit to presidential and 
congressional candidates 
if you like a campaign that involves people at the local level 
then dont go down that slippery slope of microregulation 
republican national committee counsel mark braden told the 
commission he warned that if the local parties are forced into 
complicated bookkeeping on what money is spent for federal and 
nonfederal campaigns they will probably ignore the rules or simply 
bow out of campaigning that would freeze out grassroots activity 
and shift to a total national tv campaign he said 
braden and his democratic counterpart joseph rieser jr argued 
that where federal and local goals overlap the local and state 
parties should not be saddled with complicated allocation formulas 
but should be allowed to allocate the funds to federal and 
nonfederal accounts in a way that best suits their situation 
no matter how stringent the rules the fec wont be able to 
accomplish complete fairness braden said 
you draw up the rules i get paid to manipulate them he 
said whatever you do is going to be maniplated to some degree 
rieser denied that the dnc gives money to local and state parties 
only to help the presidential race he said the party has an 
interest in local level politics as well 
different states have different political situations that would 
make it unfair to lock them into using a standard formula for how 
much of their activity benefits federal elections versus local 
elections 
for instance california had a plethora of hotlycontested ballot 
initiatives and many tight legislative races on which the state and 
local parties invested heavily for slate mailers and 
getoutthevote activity other states had little state election 
interest and were more focused on the presidential race 
the public hearing testimony was a step in fec compliance with a 
federal court order that said the commissions rules were too vague 
on soft money which is banned in federal elections but is permitted 
in many states 
soft money generally refers to union and corporate donations as 
well as individual contributions in excess of the federal limit of 
1000 such funds are banned in federal elections but permitted in 
many states 
the focus of the current fec deliberations is how the parties 
should allocate funds to soft or nonfederal accounts and to 
federal accounts for campaign activities that benefit both federal 
and nonfederal candidates such activities include voter 
registration and getoutthevote drives as well as slate cards and 
administrative costs 
fred wertheimer president of common cause a longtime critic of 
the system said that both parties in 1988 brazenly flouted the 
limits imposed by federal law on the sources and amounts of 
permissable contributions in connection with federal elections 
noting that both parties had raised millions of dollars in soft 
money he accused them of using the system to circumvent the limits 
on what they could spend for their presidential nominees by doing it 
through state party activity 
braden and rieser both said they knew of no examples of soft 
money being spent on the campaigns of george bush and democrat 
michael dukakis but they acknowledged that party spending at any 
level inevitably helps the top of the ticket 
that sort of activity affects all elections said rieser 
you cant help a legislative candidate without helping the top 
of the ticket said braden everything affects everything else 
the rnc raised in the neighborhood of 70 million this year with 
about 20 million of that in soft money braden said 
however those figures did not include another 25 million that 
was raised through the victory 88 program the rnc set up in 
each state with the funds going directly into state accounts rather 
than to the rnc 
the democrats said rieser raised about 60 million this year 
with some 18 million of that in soft money 
both parties had programs to court highdollar givers who 
contributed sums of 100000 or more 
the federal system permits an individual to give no more than 
25000 per year in federal election contributions including to 
parties and candidates but unlimited sums can be donated to 
nonfederal accounts 
</TEXT>
