<TEXT>
the illinois supreme court today threw 
out a 200000 libel verdict stemming from a 1980 editorial in the 
belleville ill newsdemocrat that said a county board chairman 
lied about his stand on a tax increase 
without written dissent the justices said the editorial 
attacking thenst clair county board chairman jerry costello was 
false and libelous but that costellos lawyer didnt prove the 
newspapers editors had reason to believe it was false when they 
published it 
as a result the high court said costello failed to meet the 
actual malice test for libel claims by public officials that 
the statement was made with the knowledge that it was false or a 
reckless disregard for the truth 
failure to investigate does not itself establish actual malice 
if the editors did not seriously doubt the truth of their 
assertions justice daniel ward wrote in the courts opinion 
costello who was elected this fall to the us house of 
representatives filed the lawsuit against capital cities 
communications inc owner of the newspaper and richard hargraves 
the editorialpage editor who wrote the editorial 
the case gained national attention in 1984 when hargraves was 
jailed briefly for refusing to reveal the names of people he said 
were confidential sources for the editorial 
the newspaper endorsed costello in his 1980 campaign for county 
board chairman saying he had promised to vigrously oppose any new 
taxes without approval by voter referendum 
after the election the county board approved a creation of a 
mass transit district with taxing powers and the newspaper blasted 
costello in a scathing editorial 
jerry costello lied to us and when he lied to us he lied 
to you the editorial said in part 
costello filed a libel lawsuit against the newspaper claiming 
that he had lobbied against the measure but as the boards presiding 
officer was barred by law from speaking or voting on the issue when 
a roll call was taken 
the lawsuit initially was dismissed by a circuit judge but a 
trial was ordered by a state appellate court costello was awarded 
600000 in punitive damages and 450000 in compensatory damages 
after the trial judge found that the editorials statements were 
false and malicious 
on appeal a divided illinois appellate court panel upheld the 
verdict for costello but threw out the punitive damage award and 
reduce the compensatory award to 200000 the majority opinion 
called the editorial unduly harsh and vicious 
however dissenting appellate judge robert steigmann wrote that 
the majority decision constitutes a threat to one of our most 
important freedoms the freedom of the press to criticize 
vigorously and even unpleasantly public officials in the execution 
of their official duties 
