<TEXT>
the number of us business failures fell by 63 
percent during the first three quarters of this year the best 
performance in nearly a decade according to a private survey 
released thursday 
the number of business failures fell to 44793 from 47794 in the 
first nine months of 1987 the report by dun amp bradstreet corp 
stated 
joseph duncan dun amp bradstreets corporate economist said the 
decline was larely attributable to decreases in the levels of 
failures in the oil and agricultural states 
agricultural business failures fell 549 percent duncan said the 
number of agricultural failures soared in 1987 when farmers took 
advantage of new protections under the federal bankruptcy law the 
rush to benefit from the new provisions subsided this year leading 
to the drop in failures in that industry 
the only industry to see an increase in failures was wholesale 
trade where 54 percent more companies failed during the first nine 
months of this year than in the same period a year earlier 
in other industries mining failures fell 255 percent 
transportation and utility failures were off 78 percent retail 
failures were off 66 percent financial insurance and real estate 
failures fell 34 percent failures of service companies were down 
18 percent construction failures were off 14 percent and 
manufacturing failures were essentially unchanged 
dun amp bradstreet is a financial information publisher 
</TEXT>
