<DOCNO> AP881215-0310 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the state legislature voted unanimously 
thursday to temporarily restore to corporations in new york a weapon 
to fight hostile takeover attempts by other companies 
the measure validating the use of socalled poison pills was 
approved 1290 by the state assembly and 520 by the senate and sent 
to gov mario cuomos desk the legislation a product of 
negotiations involving the governors office is expected to quickly 
be signed into law by cuomo 
the measure is designed to undo until april 1 1989 the result 
of a state supreme court ruling earlier this year in which a poison 
pill that irving bank corp tried to use to fend off a hostile 
takeover by bank of new york co was ruled illegal 
that court decided new york state laws prohibit the inequitable 
treatment of shareholders that cleared the way for bank of new 
yorks acquisition and raised concerns among the more than 100 
companies in new york that have poison pill rules in place as 
protection against hostile suitors 
under the poison pill scenario a target company gives 
shareholders the right to buy additional stock at reduced prices 
when an outside party buys up a certain percentage of the companys 
shares that makes it far more expensive for a suitor to buy enough 
stock to get a controlling interest in the target company 
the poison pill is designed chiefly to give a company time to 
fend off an unfriendly takeover if it chooses or to negotiate a 
better price for its shareholders if it goes along with a buyout 
offer 
the senate sponsor of the bill richard schermerhorn rorange 
said the republicancontrolled senate originally favored validating 
the poison pills for 18 months but he said that time period was 
reduced due to opposition in the democratic assembly 
a special task force made up of business leaders and others is in 
charge of studying the use of poison pills and other aspects of the 
merger and acquisition field and will report to the legislature by 
early spring 
schermerhorn said hed been told there were billions of dollars 
out there that could be used in acquisitions and that some effort 
must be made to head off the wholesale buying and selling of 
companies 
state sen franz leichter a manhattan democrat who voted for 
the measure said poison pills are sometimes used by corporate 
management to keep itself in control he said that can lead to 
what he called abuses 
poison pills really are a way of changing the rules in the 
middle of a game he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881215-0311 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal appeals court on thursday ruled that 
the leasing of two corn wet milling plants in iowa by nabisco brands 
inc to archerdanielsmidland co in 1982 was a violation of the 
sherman antitrust act 
the government had claimed in a suit filed in december 1982 that 
the lease created an unreasonable restraint of trade because it 
would give adm a large enough share of the high fructose corn syrup 
hfcs market to control the price of the product 
in the early 1970s new technology allowed the processing by wet 
corn milling plants of certain corn syrups into a substitute for 
sugar in sweetening various products including canned fruits and 
soft drinks 
the suit noted that since 1934 sugar cane and beet sugar growers 
have benefitted from either direct subsidies or sugar price supports 
enacted by congress because of the price supports the price of 
hfcs has been substantially lower than the price of sugar for many 
years 
the government presented evidence that if the lease between adm 
and nabisco was consummated adm would be able because of its newly 
established market position to raise the price of hfcs to a level 
just below the price of sugar 
the companies however were granted a summary judgment in the 
case in us district court in iowa that court agreed that sugar 
and hfcs are in the same relevant product market and that adms 
share of that market was not sufficient to constitute a violation of 
the sherman act or the clayton act 
in its 21 decision thursday a panel of the 8th us circuit 
court of appeals ruled however that while sugar and hfcs are 
functionally interchangeable they are not reasonably 
interchangeable because of the price differential between the two 
products and therefore are not in the same relevant product market 
the majority on the appeals court panel comprised judges gerald 
w heaney and theodore mcmillian 
dissenting was judge donald r ross who said he agreed with the 
district courts decision that hfcs and sugar belong in the same 
relevant product market 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

